ETL Decisions
Decision 1 — Date Standardization
Problem: The raw dataset contained inconsistent date formats such as DD/MM/YYYY and MM-DD-YYYY, making it difficult to analyze time-based trends.
Resolution: All dates were converted into a standard YYYY-MM-DD format and stored in the dim_date table with separate month and year fields for easier aggregation.

Decision 2 — Category Cleaning
Problem: Product categories had inconsistent casing such as "electronics", "Electronics", and "ELECTRONICS".
Resolution: All category values were standardized into proper case (e.g., "Electronics", "Clothing", "Groceries") to ensure consistent grouping in analytical queries.

Decision 3 — Handling Missing Values
Problem: Some records contained NULL or missing values for fields such as revenue or quantity.
Resolution: Missing numeric values were either removed or replaced with default values based on context. Only clean and complete records were inserted into the fact table to maintain data quality.
